{{Jainism}}
'''''Mahaveer Janma Kalyanak''''', is one of the most important religious festivals for [[Jain]]s. It celebrates the birth of [[Mahaveer]], the twenty-fourth and last ''[[Tirthankara]]'' of ''[[Avasarpiṇī]]''.{{efn|descending half of the worldly time cycle as per [[Jain cosmology]] which is actually current now}} As per the [[Gregorian calendar]], the holiday occurs either in March or April.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9dNOT9iYxcMC |title=Concise Encyclopaedia of India|first=K.R.|last=Gupta|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist |date= 2006|accessdate=6 May 2017|isbn=9788126906390|p=1001 }}</ref>

==Birth==
Most modern historians consider Kundagram (which is today's Kundalpur in Champaran district of Bihar) as [[Mahaveer]]'s birthplace, .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2003-10-14/patna/27173208_1_kundalpur-lord-Mahaveera-basokund|title=Row over Mahaveer’s birthplace|work=The Times of India}}</ref> According to Jain texts, Mahaveer was born on the thirteenth day of the bright half of the moon in the month of ''[[Chaitra]]'' in the year 599 BCE (Chaitra Sud 13).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=KpBuAAAAMAAJ|title=Gazetteers: Junagadh|last1=(India)|first1=Gujarat|year=1975|p=13}}</ref><ref>Kristi L. Wiley: ''Historical Dictionary of Jainism'', Lanham 2004, p. 134.</ref> Mahaveer was born in a democratic kingdom (Ganarajya), Vajji, where the king was chosen by votes. [[Vaishali district|Vaishali]] was its capital.{{sfn|Jalaj|2011|p=4}}

Mahaveer was named 'Vardhamana', which means "One who grows", because of the increased prosperity in the kingdom at the time of his birth.{{sfn|Kailash Chand Jain|1991|p=32}} In Vasokund, Mahaveer is much revered by the villagers. A place called ''Ahalya bhumi'' has not been ploughed for hundreds of years by the family that owns it, as it is considered to be the birthplace of Mahaveer.{{sfn|Jalaj|2011|p=4}}

==Birth legend==
[[File:Sixteen Symbolic Dreams.jpg|thumb|left|Sixteen auspicious dreams seen by the mother of all ''Tirthankara'']]
Mahaveer was born into [[Ikshvaku dynasty]] as the son of King [[Siddhartha of Kundagrama]] and Queen [[Trishala]]. During her pregnancy, Trishala was believed to have had a number of [[auspicious dreams]], all signifying the coming of a great soul. [[Digambara]] sect of Jainism holds that the mother saw sixteen dreams which were interpreted by the King Siddhartha.{{sfn|Pannalal Jain|2015|p=460}} According to the [[Svetambara]] sect, the total number of auspicious dreams is fourteen. It is said that when Queen Trishala gave birth to Mahaveer, [[Indra]], the head of heavenly beings (''[[Deva (Jainism)|devas]]'') performed a ritual called ''abhisheka on Sumeru Parvat'', this being the second of five auspicious events (''[[Panch Kalyanaka]]s''), said to occur in the life of all ''Tirthankaras''.<ref>{{citation|last=Pramansagar|first=Muni|title=Jain tattvavidya|year=2008|publisher=Bhartiya Gyanpeeth|location=India|isbn=978-81-263-1480-5|p=30}}</ref>

==Celebrations==
[[File:Thirakoil-mahaaveerar.JPG|Ancient image of Mahaveer at [[Thirakoil]]|thumb|250px|right]]
The idol of Mahaveer is carried out on a chariot, in a procession called ''rath yatra''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/469429/piety-marks-mahaveer-jayanthi.html|title=Piety marks Mahaveer Jayanthi|work=Deccan Herald}}</ref> On the way stavans (religious rhymes) are recited.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freepressjournal.in/both-sects-of-jain-community-take-out-attractive-joint-procession/|title=Both sects of Jain community take out attractive joint procession|publisher=|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406193847/http://www.freepressjournal.in/both-sects-of-jain-community-take-out-attractive-joint-procession/|archivedate=6 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Statues of Mahaveer are given a ceremonial anointment called the [[Abhisheka#Abhisheka as a ritual|''abhisheka'']].  During the day, most members of the [[Jain community]] engage in some sort of charitable act, prayers, pujas, and vratas. Many devotees visit temples dedicated to Mahaveer to meditate and offer prayers.<ref>{{citation |title=Mahaveer Jayanti 2015: The importance of a Satvik meal |url=http://food.ndtv.com/food-drinks/mahavir-jayanti-2015-the-importance-of-a-satvik-meal-751655 |work=[[NDTV]] |date=2 April 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404075153/http://food.ndtv.com/food-drinks/mahavir-jayanti-2015-the-importance-of-a-satvik-meal-751655 |archivedate=4 April 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Lectures by monks and nuns are held in temples to preach the path of virtue as defined by [[Jainism]]. Donations are collected in order to promote charitable missions like saving cows from slaughter or helping to feed poor people. Ancient Jain temples across India typically see an extremely high volume of practitioners come to pay their respects and join in the celebrations.{{cn|date=March 2017}}

Ahimsa runs and rallies preaching the Mahaveer's message of [[Ahimsa in Jainism|Ahiṃsā]] (non-violence of non-injury) are taken out on this day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merinews.com/article/jain-youth-to-hold-vegan-promotion-rally-on-mahavir-jayanti-in-pink-city-jaipur/15905383.shtml|title=Jain youth to hold vegan promotion rally on Mahaveer Jayanti in pink city Jaipur|work=merinews.com |date=28 March 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report-jains-gear-up-for-mahavir-jayanti-tomorrow-2073618|title=Jains gear up for Mahaveer Janma Kalyanak tomorrow|date=1 April 2015|work=dnaindia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/over-900-run-for-spreading-bhagwan-mahaveers-message/article7047517.ece|title=Over 900 run for spreading Bhagwan Mahaveer’s message|author=Staff Reporter|work=The Hindu |date=30 March 2015 }}</ref>

